NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I am a "lead your best unbid suit" believer against NT, so I think Betty should lead a spade. The only question is which spade. In general, either 4th best or top of a 3 card honor sequence. But with her particular holding Betty should lead the @SK. The lead of the king against NT is not necessarily top of a sequence (although it often is).|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The lead of the King asks partner for attitude about the suit. If East leads the @SK, West should play the @S6 to hopefully encourage a spade continuation. The 6 should look encouraging (the 5 and 4 are missing) so East should continue with the @S9. West should overtake and lead back a spade. They take 4 spade tricks.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The lead of the ace against NT is very rare. Traditionally, and the way I play it, is that the lead of the ace in NT means partner should drop an honor (jack or higher) if they have it. The most common holding where the ace is led is something like AKJ10 where dropping the queen is useful.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Lacking an honor (which is what happens most of the time) partner should give count. In summary, the lead of an ace against NT asks partner to a) drop an honor or b) if no honor give count.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


