cp|8|AT|

 ^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There are 2 answers to that.
^C@2The first is, don't worry about that, because there are very few hands where you want to play 2@D rather than 1NT. But if you want to play the expert version of 2 way Checkback which I explain next. |
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The 2nd answer is, if responder bids 2@C over 1N, opener MUST bid 2@D. No ifs ands or buts. Then you can stop in 2@D. So if you prefer the expert way, you can stop in 2@D.|
PG| ***** 36 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The "xyz" is an extension of 2 way Checkback so named because it applies whenever the auction starts 1x-1y-1z. There is a 1-level opener, responder bids at the 1-level, and opener rebids at the 1-level. For example, if you play "xyz" it applies if the auction starts 1@C-P-1@H-P-1@S or 1@D-P-1@H-P-1@S.|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Over 1@S, 2@C is an artificial game invitation and 2@D is an artificial game force. It is a lot more complicated, however, because there are many more auctions it applies to and the follow ups depend on how the auction starts. |
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I recommend:
^C@2a) start with 1 way Checkback over 1NT (e.g. 2@C is always asking about majors whether opener started with 1@C or not).|
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


NT|^c@2
b) if you want to get adventurous, try 2 way Checkback after a while. the recent Bergen audio lesson is a great learning tool. Check the link given earlier by nome (Kia).|
